The names are nearly all horrowed from Homer, but they do not designate the same persons; eg„ the four in line 767 are killed by Ulysses in the Iliad, and Homer's Clytius is a son of Laomedon. Phegeus was associated with Sagaris as a famulus in V. 263 (see note on line 569), but we cannot with any confidence identify these subordinate personages‚ as in Book XII. we find Turnus killing again a Phegeus (371, seq.)‚ an Amycus (509), and a Cretheus (538), while a Clytius who is a mere lad is found in Book X. (32 5). Amycus is mentioned in Book 1. 221 as a friend especially esteemed by Aeneas, and the name is also applied to a Bithynian prince in V. 373.
